07:29.215 --> 07:34.462
was far more concerned about big changes. And and 
was somewhat lethargic in embracing some of the

07:38.643 --> 07:44.631
changes. Were you one of the more, using the word 
liberal now as receptive to change, do you think

07:45.572 --> 07:54.323
you were seen as one of the more liberal deans at 
that point? I think so, Haskell.

08:00.852 --> 08:07.080
In fact, a few years later, when...

08:08.107 --> 08:20.008
The then College of Arts and Sciences was 
reorganized into a College of Science and a

08:08.107 --> 08:20.008
College of Liberal Arts. There was some concern 
among

08:22.613 --> 08:31.549
key administrators, the top ones, about the use of 
the word liberal arts. Really, really. And in

08:39.424 --> 08:47.891
fact, I was asked if I had considered a College of 
Humanities as the title.

08:53.015 --> 09:02.363
But the College of Liberal Arts title prevailed 
and was finally accepted, although there, there

09:02.798 --> 09:08.243
was some skepticism about the word liberal in the 
liberal arts. I was asked at a retreat for

09:10.366 --> 09:27.022
administrators that was held up near Teague, 
Texas at some utilities company meeting house. I

09:28.624 --> 09:32.788
was asked, why is it that you people in the liberal 
arts are always the ones who raise cane around

09:34.017 --> 09:39.625
here.

09:49.961 --> 09:51.463
It was an interesting session. I introduced my 
colleagues to the trivium

09:51.483 --> 10:02.860
and the quadrivium from Greek and Roman times when 
the liberal arts were first expressed in those

10:03.852 --> 10:11.885
terms. And it was intended to be a serious

10:12.986 --> 10:26.147
effort on the part of knowledge purveyors to 
embrace those basic disciplines which were

10:26.988 --> 10:48.692
non-vocational in nature and which in fact would 
free, thus liberal, would free the individual

10:26.988 --> 10:48.692
from having to participate in menial types of jobs 
and effort, et cetera.

10:51.895 --> 10:55.459
I was much better prepared on that occasion than I 
am now to elaborate upon that early development of

10:56.182 --> 11:05.419
the liberal arts through the trivium and the 
quadrivium. But it was, I think, an eye-opener for

11:06.741 --> 11:15.517
some of my colleagues. And I think they felt better 
about it after that

11:22.372 --> 11:34.787
effort on my part to explain the essence and nature 
of the studies which comprise the liberal arts

11:22.372 --> 11:34.787
sector. Now, the work of the Aspirations 
Committee took more than a year. It and all of its

11:40.894 --> 11:44.719
subunits that we call the working parties. Were 
you and your colleagues in the administration

11:45.660 --> 11:51.687
aware of some of the probable recommendations 
before the aspirations report was finished? I

11:57.279 --> 11:59.261
don't recall that we were, Haskell. Weren't 
supposed to be. I don't recall that we were at all.

12:03.765 --> 12:16.997
When the report was finished and the 
recommendation for co-education, voluntary

12:03.765 --> 12:16.997
core, racial integration and so forth, what were 
the initial reactions of the people that you

12:03.765 --> 12:16.997
recall? Mixed. There was still among the members 
of the Century Council some true original

12:20.219 --> 12:49.534
Aggies who did not support wholeheartedly the 
move to coeducational and to a voluntary

12:20.219 --> 12:49.534
military. they did not take it easily. And I'm 
going to say among this number, there may have been

12:57.068 --> 13:09.465
half a dozen out of the 100 who

12:57.068 --> 13:09.465
constituted the members of the Century Council. 
But

13:10.246 --> 13:20.500
they did not indicate that they wanted to present a 
minority report. And I think Harold Dunn's

13:21.830 --> 13:36.109
leadership in that regard was another key element 
in the success of the conclusion of the study. The

13:38.652 --> 13:50.267
final report then, who were some of the strongest 
supporters on campus that you recall to endorse

13:38.652 --> 13:50.267
it? Oh, on campus? Yes,

13:51.943 --> 13:56.551
sir. I think it was pretty universally accepted 
and supported, Haskell. I can't point out any

14:02.501 --> 14:11.456
single voices that were strongest in its support. 
Those who might have been

14:19.762 --> 14:26.670
slow to accept it, were quiet, as I recall. Mr. 
Rutter, as far as you know, his initial reaction? I

14:31.976 --> 14:34.219
think it was favorable, Haskell, yes. Now, I 
understand from Wayne Hall that one of the

14:35.440 --> 14:44.171
recommendations that bothered Mr. Rutter was 
leaving the A&M out of the title. Yes, that would

14:44.191 --> 14:47.895
have... been a great concern to him. He wanted the 
A&M brand

14:52.713 --> 14:59.723
locked in. Do you remember any attempt by any board 
member to

15:00.784 --> 15:10.238
contradict or counteract anything? No. No, I 
don't recall at all. Now, as I look back on that

15:14.804 --> 15:17.308
board, I say to a number of observers that Mr. 
Rutter was fortunate in that he had a number of

15:18.183 --> 15:29.137
people on the board then who had had major 
management experience. Yes. And that that helped

15:30.238 --> 15:33.602
them not to be nitpickers and micromanagers. Yes. 
Let's see. Was the chairman of the board of

15:37.126 --> 15:42.733
Tentaco, was he on board by that time? I think so. 
And Sterling Evans. And Dow Chemical. Dow

15:46.583 --> 15:47.724
Chemical, Boyle. Vice President. Boyle. Al 
Davies, former CEO of Sears. Yes. Dick Goodson,

15:53.871 --> 15:55.713
former CEO of Southwestern. Yes. Oh, yes. These 
are great names, and they were strongly

15:57.275 --> 16:04.803
supportive of the council study. All right. As the 
aspirations, I mean, as those recommendations

16:06.304 --> 16:16.135
began to take effect, share some experiences you 
may recall as to the effects at the working level of

16:16.773 --> 16:24.061
women enrolling and of black students being 
admitted? It

16:24.081 --> 16:40.620
was a period of,

16:24.081 --> 16:40.620
at the working level, in the office, at the desk,

16:44.077 --> 16:45.700
keeping the network alive. It was a rapid pace 
environment. Things were happening so rapidly.

16:55.739 --> 16:57.522
Enrollment picked up quickly. Space was a 
problem.

17:03.449 --> 17:05.912
Women were delightful. They added such a great new 
chemistry to the campus, a great new

17:06.513 --> 17:13.984
characteristic. Do you remember any anecdotes to 
illustrate that? No. No, I don't. It was just so

17:24.779 --> 17:29.085
fine to have them aboard. I think it helped with

17:30.668 --> 17:43.281
the behavior of the student body general. In the 
presence of a lady, one tends to be more careful

17:44.502 --> 17:58.296
with one's behavior and language and so forth, and 
I think in that regard it was a great additive to the

17:44.502 --> 17:58.296
campus. That's not to say that before they came 
there was not an

17:58.580 --> 18:13.743
acceptable level of performance in that regard, 
but they added that element.

18:18.830 --> 18:24.098
I was concerned about getting new curricula 
going. I was concerned, and this is without regard

18:25.293 --> 18:29.841
to women and minorities. This was with respect to 
the essential components of a college of liberal

18:30.001 --> 18:38.535
arts. I was concerned about getting a philosophy 
department going. That was my number one

18:43.423 --> 18:47.550
ambition, a department of philosophy. I dearly 
wanted to see it come about. I also wanted at

18:53.778 --> 18:57.122
another level. I wanted to get geography out of 
agriculture.

19:04.211 --> 19:05.012
And that happened. How did you do that?

19:09.457 --> 19:10.779
Simply mainly by. Indicating to the front office 
that it needed to be done. And I had some at that time

19:17.527 --> 19:20.511
Ed. Duran, a geographer, I think was supportive of 
the idea. Smith, as I recall, who had been in

19:28.937 --> 19:43.755
geography with Schleselmann many, many years, 
was supportive of it, and he was an old liner in the

19:28.937 --> 19:43.755
College of Agriculture. So that happened. Where 
did you get the resources for philosophy?

19:50.883 --> 19:53.185
Interesting, it came about in this way. At that 
time, early 60s and far beyond earlier,

19:55.807 --> 20:14.665
the several churches on the periphery of the 
campus offered courses in the Bible. The courses

20:17.107 --> 20:20.670
were built into the catalog They were placed in the 
catalog in such a way that they were

20:20.988 --> 20:37.895
non-denominational, thereby exempting their 
offering from being criticized as

20:20.988 --> 20:37.895
denominationalism.

20:41.761 --> 20:47.670
And almost every, I think almost every sect around 
the campus had its campus minister who taught a

20:48.376 --> 20:54.445
course. And they taught the course in their 
building, not on campus.

21:01.655 --> 21:05.601
Now here's the trick they added to make it purely 
denominational. In the battalion, each semester

21:06.542 --> 21:14.974
before registration, they would run a little 
block advertisement saying,

21:19.122 --> 21:24.489
I don't know what the tag was for religion. Was it 
religion itself? Or was it humanities? I don't

21:30.676 --> 21:31.177
know. But we'll say it was religion. Religion 101, 
the Old Testament. Section 21,

21:37.906 --> 21:47.037
Father Donahoe. location in the Catholic Student 
Union, well, you know, that's, and likewise for

21:48.873 --> 22:08.516
each other, each other denomination or sector of 
the churches around the campus. And under the

22:08.736 --> 22:16.886
Coordinating Board formula system, that earned 
some student credit hour dollars for Texas A&M.

22:17.527 --> 22:17.867
Yes. Now then, I learned on one occasion, and I 
picked this up through the registrar's office, I

22:19.062 --> 22:49.052
think I got a tip from, I don't know that it was Lloyd 
Heaton himself or someone in the registrar's

22:19.062 --> 22:49.052
office, that in one of these classes in religion 
being offered off campus, and I must say I honestly

22:19.062 --> 22:49.052
do not recall which

22:49.589 --> 23:08.598
which church it was associated with, there was a 
prof, a campus minister teaching the course

22:49.589 --> 23:08.598
who was very

22:49.589 --> 23:08.598
liberal in student comings and goings. You really 
didn't have to attend. And there were some

23:13.085 --> 23:17.892
students who would register, I'm told, I was told 
at the time, some students who would register for

23:18.462 --> 23:26.790
the course and during an entire semester might 
attend five times. Then at the end of the course

23:28.832 --> 23:37.460
would receive a passing grade of A or B and get 
credit for it.

23:42.985 --> 23:47.389
I verified this information, then took it to 
President Rutter I says, we're open for a lot of

23:47.707 --> 23:54.816
serious embarrassment over this situation. And 
we need to reclaim these courses in religion and

23:56.478 --> 24:15.163
get them taught on campus by people whom we select, 
whom we exercise some authority over. And We need

24:19.162 --> 24:20.523
to do it quickly. He says, you think it's that bad? I 
said, yes, sir, I certainly do. It would just take

24:25.148 --> 24:35.919
one newspaper to pick it up from somewhere from the 
battalion and what we're doing, and it would be so

24:25.148 --> 24:35.919
embarrassing. He said, what shall we do? I says, we 
need to create a department of philosophy.

24:46.290 --> 24:46.931
And we did. He said, OK. Who are you going to get to 
run it? I said, I'll employ someone. I'll go to the

24:54.698 --> 24:56.701
key places and find. Among the searches that I made 
for our first department head in philosophy, I

24:56.721 --> 25:07.219
went to Yale.

25:13.691 --> 25:14.532
There I met. I had corresponded with him earlier. I 
met John Orr, O-R-R, brilliant young guy,

25:17.992 --> 25:40.266
Presbyterian, incidentally, and he had just 
finished his doctorate in philosophy, and he had

25:17.992 --> 25:40.266
also had his, he had been in the Yale program of I 
don't know whether they call it a divinity or a

25:41.242 --> 26:09.055
seminary or what but He had been through that 
Excellent program in religion and had his degree

25:41.242 --> 26:09.055
there along with his doctorate in philosophy So I 
thought that would make him more acceptable to the

25:41.242 --> 26:09.055
campus ministers having that background

25:41.242 --> 26:09.055
I Met with the ministers told them of our plans and 
that we were going to bring the Department of

26:09.676 --> 26:24.171
Philosophy on board and that when we did, we would 
discontinue the off-campus offerings. They

26:24.191 --> 26:25.592
accepted it okay. I think they were aware all the 
time that

26:27.174 --> 26:38.485
it was an

26:27.174 --> 26:38.485
unsafe situation. John Orr came aboard, did a 
great job as a one-man department. He was

26:45.283 --> 26:47.886
department head and faculty the first year. 
Students hearing about it and registering for the

26:49.747 --> 26:59.396
courses just became thirsty for it, Haskell, 
really excited about the language and

26:49.747 --> 26:59.396
philosophy. And next year I think John employed 
Manuel Davenport. I think Manuel came from One of

27:08.958 --> 27:13.843
the California schools, I want to say, but he came 
with excellent credentials. He was had received.

27:19.089 --> 27:24.194
I think at his institution that which was called 
the Albert Schweitzer. Award for teaching.

27:31.062 --> 27:36.788
Made a great impression during the interview and 
we brought him on board and excellent for the

27:37.004 --> 27:39.266
department all the way through. So we got the 
Department of Philosophy started in that

27:39.306 --> 27:45.332
fashion.

27:49.896 --> 27:50.516
Let's see. Then it was time to separate education 
and psychology. We did not have on the campus at

27:59.885 --> 28:04.429
that time any

28:06.181 --> 28:15.897
practicing experimental psychologist

28:06.181 --> 28:15.897
or a clinical psychologist. That was far, far out 
of reach for us. But we needed an experimentalist

28:20.003 --> 28:33.285
who could do some basic research and teaching in 
the field of psychology and ultimately work

28:20.003 --> 28:33.285
toward a degree in psychology.

28:37.687 --> 28:41.210
Again, another interesting development. At that 
time, Dr. Sidney O. Brown, professor in the

28:45.474 --> 29:07.693
Department of Biology, had a contract with the 
United States Air Force doing research on goats,

28:45.474 --> 29:07.693
tracking physiological changes in goats after 
they had been exposed to low doses of radiation out

29:08.635 --> 29:22.294
at our nuclear science center, actually built a 
goat shed out there, pens and goats.

29:24.477 --> 29:37.275
He would expose the animals to low doses of 
radiation, then would examine them and their

29:24.477 --> 29:37.275
carcasses closely. The results were just from 
well received by the Air Force. This is great

29:44.788 --> 29:45.970
stuff. And they came back to Dr. Brown after a 
couple of years of this research and they asked

29:46.630 --> 29:56.443
him, Dr. Brown, will you add another dimension to 
your research? And that is, we'd like to know what

29:56.543 --> 30:03.172
behavioral changes take place. Brown says, 
that's not my field, but I'll see about adding a

30:09.925 --> 30:22.204
staff member to my research team who's an 
experimental psychologist and see if we can't get

30:09.925 --> 30:22.204
into that field. Brown came to me and said, told me 
this story that had been asked of him. And he said,

30:30.717 --> 30:37.688
I'd like to, he says, I think I can, I know a 
connection over at the University of Texas. where

30:38.343 --> 30:52.243
I can go over there and get them to let me have a 
half-time psychologist to come over here,

30:38.343 --> 30:52.243
appropriate intervals, and assist me in 
research.

30:55.908 --> 31:01.195
I said, have

30:55.908 --> 31:01.195
you made any contacts there yet? No, I have not. I 
said, let me make a suggestion. If your contract

31:07.368 --> 31:14.699
will pay for half of a faculty person, I'll pay the 
other half. Let's bring him here full time on that

31:14.719 --> 31:22.931
basis and have him begin teaching some courses in 
experimental psychology. Good. Brown was

31:24.473 --> 31:29.100
receptive to the idea and we did that. At that time, 
Dr. Walter Varvel, was the principal

31:34.199 --> 31:46.752
psychologist I felt on campus, and he was in the 
Department of Educational Psychology teaching

31:34.199 --> 31:46.752
counseling courses and doing it admirably. His

31:46.792 --> 31:58.124
degree, however, had been in experimental 
psychology, as I recall, University of Kansas.

32:01.948 --> 32:03.430
I asked him for his help. in finding an 
experimentalist, a young person who could team up

32:03.933 --> 32:10.160
with John Orr. No, not with John Orr, but with 
Sidney Brown, and do this work. Of course, he did a

32:19.390 --> 32:21.272
natural thing. He first contacted, I think, the 
University of Kansas. They gave him glowing

32:24.996 --> 32:29.962
remarks about a young doctorate named Casey. Ben 
Casey or Albert Casey? Albert, one of the two. He

32:39.103 --> 32:40.024
came aboard. And I often say that, well, not often, 
but I sometimes say that

32:40.044 --> 32:59.212
our psychology department grew out of a goat 
research experiment. That's not too well

32:59.232 --> 33:03.758
received, but I think it has some basis in fact. But 
it's good for a land grant school that it grew out of

33:04.058 --> 33:10.047
a goat herd. Yes.

33:13.892 --> 33:17.578
Another interesting development at this time, 
Haskell.

